  "local_port": 47756,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What social media etiquette do we often forget?",
  "response": "Social media etiquette is crucial for maintaining positive interactions online, yet certain aspects are often overlooked. Here are some common social media etiquette rules people tend to forget:\n\n1. **Overposting or Oversharing**  \n   Posting too frequently or sharing overly personal details can overwhelm your audience and come across as inconsiderate.\n\n2. **Not Fact-Checking Before Sharing**  \n   Sharing unverified information or fake news can spread misinformation and harm your credibility.\n\n3. **Ignoring Comments or Messages**  \n   Failing to acknowledge or respond to comments or direct messages can seem dismissive or rude.\n\n4. **Overusing Hashtags**  \n   Using too many hashtags can make posts look spammy and reduce engagement.\n\n5. **Tagging People Without Permission**  \n   Tagging others in posts or photos without their consent can invade their privacy or annoy them.\n\n6. **Posting Irrelevant Content**  \n   Sharing content unrelated to the platform or audience can seem out of touch or inconsiderate.\n\n7. **Engaging in Arguments**  \n   Getting into heated debates or bullying others in comments or messages reflects poorly on you and creates negativity.\n\n8. **Not Giving Credit**  \n   Sharing someone else\u2019s work (e.g., photos, quotes, or ideas) without attribution is disrespectful and can lead to copyright issues.\n\n9. **Overposting About Yourself**  \n   Constantly promoting yourself or your achievements without acknowledging others can come across as self-centered.\n\n10. **Ignoring the Right to Disconnect**  \n    Bombarding people with messages or expecting immediate responses disregards their personal time and boundaries.\n\n11. **Posting in Inappropriate Times**  \n    Posting late at night or early in the morning without considering your audience\u2019s time zones can be disruptive.\n\n12. **Neglecting Professionalism on LinkedIn**  \n    Sharing overly casual or irrelevant content on LinkedIn can harm your professional reputation.\n\n13. **Not Asking Before Adding to Groups**  \n    Adding people to group chats or online communities without their consent can be intrusive.\n\n14. **Ignoring Platform-Specific Norms**  \n    Each platform has its own culture and expectations\u2014posting the same content everywhere may not resonate well.\n\n15. **Baiting for Engagement**  \n    Using clickbait titles or manipulative tactics to gain likes or comments can alienate your audience.\n\nBy being mindful of these often-forgotten etiquette rules, you can foster more respectful and meaningful interactions on social media.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
